vectorData.altText: Many skeletal elements originate embryologically as cartilaginous models that are subsequently ossified. Endochondral ossification is principally responsible for the formation of long and short bones.

Hyaline cartilage model of long bone grows via interstitial     and appositional      means.
Undifferentiated mesenchymal cells of the perichondrium around the diaphysis differentiate into osteoblasts and form the bone collar via intramembranous bone formation; diaphyseal chondrocytes undergo apoptosis; cartilage matrix degenerates and calcifies
Blood vessels, CT invade diaphysis in response to VEGF      secreted by deteriorating chondrocytes; brings mesenchymal cells, which differentiate into osteoblasts; osteoblasts deposit bone matrix onto calcified cartilage in primary ossification centre.
Interstitial Growth of Cartilage: “growth from within”

cartilage, like all connective tissue types, develops from condensations of embryonic CT, called mesenchyme
where cartilage is to form, mesenchymal cells differentiate into chondroblasts, which secrete the organic components of the matrix
chondroblasts ultimately surround themselves with matrix, move apart, thus becoming isolated in their lacunae
these chondroblasts may divide, forming isogenous cell groups, which go on to secrete matrix and grow apart, while adding to the thickness of the developing cartilage
isolated chondroblastsbecome quiescent,maintain matrix aschondrocytes
Appositional Growth of Cartilage: “growth at the surface”

Appositional growth of cartilage occurs at the surface of the newly-forming cartilage, rather than from within its core, as occurs in interstitial growth of cartilage. 
mesenchymal cells at the surface of the newly formed cartilage differentiate into fibroblasts, which secrete collagen type I and form the fibrous layer of the perichondrium
mesenchymal cells deep to this fibrous layer differentiate into chondroblasts, forming the cellular layer of the perichondrium
chondroblasts secrete cartilage matrix onto the surface of the newly forming cartilage in a process called appositional growth; this increases the thickness of the cartilage by adding matrix to the surface of the growing cartilage
mesenchymal cells even deeper within the cartilage may  be undergoing interstitial growth; i.e. both processes may go on simultaneously in a growing cartilage
